As can be seen in Fig. (\ref{fig:diffract_movie}) the asymptotic behavior is as expected.  For the completely quantum case, $\epsilon = 1$, the diffraction pattern that forms is identical to the analytic case, Eq. (\ref{eqn:wf_double_t}).  For the completely classical case, $\epsilon = 0$, The diffraction pattern that forms is just that of the initial distribution, Eq. (\ref{eqn:double_init_prob}).

For all values of $0 < \epsilon \leq 1$, given enough time, a far-field diffraction pattern will develop with a visibility of one.  The time for a diffraction pattern to develop increases to infinity as degree of quantumness diminishes, $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$.  The diffraction patterns for the higher values of $\epsilon$ are less developed that for the lower values, but the visibility for all of them is one.  Fig. (\ref{fig:diffract_movie}) shows that the linear Schr\"{o}dinger equation with a scaled $\hbar$ produces completely equivalent results to the numerically solved non-linear transition equation.

\section{Macroscopic Quantum Behavior}

There is a macroscopic system that exhibits quantum behavior, that of a droplet bouncing on a vibrating bath.  It reproduces many of the phenomena we consider only to be in the domain of quantum mechanics such as an uncertainty principle, single particle diffraction and Landau levels.  It has the possibility to be a powerful tool to explore the transition between the quantum and classical worlds.  We show here how the transition equation might help describe it.

Fort et al. \cite{bib:couder_orbits} recreated, using the droplet arrangement with a spinning bath,  an analogue to the Landau levels with radii, $\rho_n$, given by:

\begin{eqnarray}
\rho_n =  \sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi}} \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{h}{q B}} \nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

%\begin{eqnarray}
%\rho_n =  \sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi}} \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{h}{q B}} \nonumber \\
%\frac{\rho_n}{\lambda_{DB}} =  \sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi}} \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{m}{q B}\frac{V}{\lambda_{DB}}} \label{eqn:landau}
%\end{eqnarray}

In the experiment by Fort et al. they measured the quantity $R_n / \lambda_{F}$ where $R_n$ is the radius from the center of the bath and $\lambda_{F}$ is the Faraday frequency.   They compare this value to $\rho_n / \lambda_{DB}$ where $\lambda_{DB}$ is the de Broglie wavelength.  Fort et al. assume $1 / (2 \Omega)$ is the equivalent to the Larmour period $\tau_L = m / (q B)$ and that the de Broglie relation, $\lambda_{DB} = h / (m V)$, holds true with the wavelength instead being the Faraday wavelength, $\lambda_{F} = h / (m V_w)$.  [What is $\Omega$ and $V_w$?]  The two equations they compared are:

\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\rho_n}{\lambda_{DB}} &=&  \sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi}} \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{m}{q B}\frac{V}{\lambda_{DB}}} \label{eqn:landau} \\
\frac{R_n}{\lambda_{F}} &=&  b \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{1}{2 \Omega}\frac{V_w}{\lambda_{F}}} \label{eqn:couder}
\end{eqnarray}

%Where the de Broglie relation $\lambda_{DB} = h / (m V)$ was used.  Fort et al. finds that the orbital radius, $R_n$ in their experiment conforms to:
%
%\begin{eqnarray}
%\frac{R_n}{\lambda_{DB}} =  b \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{1}{2 \Omega}\frac{V_w}{\lambda_{F}}} \label{eqn:couder}
%\end{eqnarray}

%Where an analogue to the de Broglie relation was used with $\lambda_{F} = \lambda_{DB}$.  Eqn. \ref{eqn:couder} fit the date with the prefactor $b = 0.89$ which is different from the prefactor in eqn. \ref{eqn:landau} of $\sqrt{1 / \pi}$.  We can use the transition equation to explain the prefactor difference.  If Fort et al. instead used the de Broglie relation with a scaled $h$, $\lambda_{F} = \sqrt{\epsilon} h / (m V_w)$ and kept the given prefactor of eqn. \ref{eqn:couder} transforms into:

Eqs. (\ref{eqn:landau}) and (\ref{eqn:couder}) match very well except for the prefactor which Fort et al. determined to be $b = 0.89$ instead of $\sqrt{1/\pi} = 0.564$.  We can use the transition equation to help explain this prefactor difference.  If the system has some classical nature to it then it will obey the transition equation instead of the Schr\"{o}dinger equation.  We have shown that using the transition equation is equivalent to using the Schr\"{o}dinger equation with a rescaled $\tilde{h} = \sqrt{\epsilon} h$, therefore  if Fort et al. instead used the de Broglie relation with a scaled $h$, $\lambda_{F} = \tilde{h} / (m V_w) = \sqrt{\epsilon} h / (m V_w)$ and kept the given prefactor of $\sqrt{1/\pi}$, Eq. (\ref{eqn:couder}) becomes:

\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{R_n}{\lambda_{DB}} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi \sqrt{\epsilon}}} \sqrt{(n + \frac{1}{2})\frac{1}{2 \Omega}\frac{V_w}{\lambda_{F}}} \label{eqn:couderscaled} \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}

Therefore, $b = \sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi \sqrt{\epsilon}}}$, which gives a degree of quantumness of $\epsilon = 0.16$, a value obviously between the classical and quantum world as we might expect for a macroscopic experiment.

%It may be worthwhile to model systems with classical components such as the droplet system by using the transition equation instead of the Schr\"{o}dinger equation.

\section{Conclusion}

We have demonstrate both analytically and numerically that it is not necessary to get rid of the classicality-enforcing potential to recover quantum behavior.  We have found that by scaling and not necessarily eliminating the classicality-enforcing potential the linear Schr\"{o}dinger equation is recovered, but with a rescaled $\hbar$.


